{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181014214752|864066035","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Evan_Jenkins_(politician)","to":"Evan Jenkins (politician)"}],"pages":{"5148038":{"pageid":5148038,"ns":0,"title":"Evan Jenkins (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-14T21:48:45Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{pp-pc1}}\n{{about|the U.S. politician|other uses|Evan Jenkins (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Evan Jenkins\n|image           = Evan Jenkins official congressional photo.jpg\n|office          = Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia|West Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals]]\n|term_start      = October 1, 2018\n|term_end        = \n|predecessor     = [[Robin Davis]]\n|successor       = \n|state1          = [[West Virginia]]\n|district1       = {{ushr|WV|3|3rd}}\n|term_start1     = January 3, 2015\n|term_end1       = September 30, 2018\n|predecessor1    = [[Nick Rahall]]\n|successor1      = ''Vacant''\n|state_senate2   = West Virginia\n|district2       = 5th\n|alongside2      = [[Robert H. Plymale]]\n|term_start2     = December 1, 2002\n|term_end2       = December 1, 2014\n|predecessor2    = [[Marie Redd]]\n|successor2      = [[Mike Woelfel]]\n|state_delegate3 = West Virginia\n|district3       = 16th\n|alongside3      = Jody Smirl, Susan Hubbard\n|term_start3     = December 1, 1994\n|term_end3       = December 1, 2000\n|predecessor3    = [[Stephen T. Williams]]\n|successor3      = [[Dale Stephens (politician)|Dale Stephens]]\n|birth_name      = Evan Hollin Jenkins\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1960|9|12}}\n|birth_place     = {{nowrap|[[Huntington, West Virginia]], U.S.}}\n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|party           = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] (Before 1992,<br>2013\u2013present)<br>[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (1992\u20132013)\n|spouse          = Elizabeth Weiler\n|children        = 3\n|education       = [[University of Florida]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Samford University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website         = {{url|evanjenkins.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Evan Hollin Jenkins''' (born September 12, 1960) is an American politician serving as Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia]] since 2018. He has served as a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from West Virginia from 2015 to 2018. He is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], having switched his party affiliation from Democrat in 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/07/evan-jenkins-party-switch-2014-election-094972|title=Dem joins GOP to run against Rahall|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-06-02}}</ref>\n\nJenkins was a member of the [[West Virginia Senate]] from the 5th District, which contains [[Cabell County, West Virginia|Cabell County]] and a small portion of [[Wayne County, West Virginia|Wayne County]].  He served in both chambers of the [[West Virginia Legislature]] in Charleston over the course of 20 years, having been elected as a member of the House in 1994, and elected to the Senate in 2002.<ref name=\"Jim Workman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wowktv.com/story/25508919/rahall-jenkins-set-to-face-off-in-3rd-district-congressional-race|title=Rahall, Jenkins set to face off in 3rd District Congressional Ra \u2013 WOWK 13 Charleston, Huntington WV News, Weather, Sports|author=Jim Workman|date=May 13, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref> He gave up his seat to run in the  2014 congressional election, defeating incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Nick Rahall]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/222908-rahall-loses-house-seat-in-west-virginia|title=Dem Rahall loses House seat after 38 years|author=Timothy Cama|work=TheHill}}</ref>\n\nJenkins was a candidate for the [[U.S. Senate]] in [[United States Senate election in West Virginia, 2018|2018]], losing to [[West Virginia Attorney General]] [[Patrick Morrisey]] in the primary election.<ref>https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/patrick-morrisey-wins-west-virginia-gop-senate-primary</ref> Jenkins is currently a candidate in the election to be held on November 6, 2018 to fill the remaining six years term as a Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia]] due to the resignation of [[Robin Davis]].<ref>http://wvmetronews.com/2018/08/14/more-candidates-lining-up-to-run-for-open-supreme-court-seats/</ref> \n\nOn September 30, 2018, Jenkins resigned from Congress, after having been appointed Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia]] by [[West Virginia Governor]] [[Jim Justice]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/evan-jenkins-to-resign-sunday|title=Evan Jenkins to Resign Seat on Sunday, Head to West Virginia Supreme Court|work=Roll Call|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJenkins, a lifelong resident of [[Huntington, West Virginia|Huntington]], is the son of Dorothy C. Jenkins and the late John E. Jenkins Jr.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wvgop.org/wv-state-legislators?page=6|title=Office Holders|work=West Virginia Republican Party|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"W.Va. Senate 5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/elections/x874711592/W-Va-Senate-5|title=W.Va. Senate 5|work=The Herald-Dispatch|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://teapartycheer.com/bios/the-south/west-virginia/evan-jenkins-wv-bio/|title=Evan Jenkins (R-WV-3)|work=Tea Party Cheer|accessdate=October 2, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006130300/http://teapartycheer.com/bios/the-south/west-virginia/evan-jenkins-wv-bio/|archive-date=October 6, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  He attended public schools.<ref name=\"W.Va. Senate 5\"/>\n\nJenkins earned his B.S. in Education/Business Administration from the [[University of Florida]] in 1983.<ref name=\"W.Va. Senate 5\"/><ref name=\"Jenkins confirms run for Congress\">{{cite web|url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/news/x1294062654/Jenkins-confirms-run-for-Congress|title=Jenkins confirms run for Congress|work=The Herald-Dispatch|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref>  He went on to earn his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Cumberland School of Law]] in 1987.<ref name=\"Jenkins confirms run for Congress\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knoxvillebusinessvoice.com/voter-resources/official/200049/Evan/Jenkins|title=State Senator Evan Jenkins (Republican Party) \u2013 Knoxville Chamber|publisher=|accessdate=October 2, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006080236/http://www.knoxvillebusinessvoice.com/voter-resources/official/200049/Evan/Jenkins|archive-date=October 6, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe was the Executive Director of the West Virginia State Medical Association, and taught [[business law]] as an instructor at [[Marshall University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/03/nick-rahall-2014_n_5259426.html|title=Longtime Dem Congressman Faces Tough 2014 Reelection Fight|date=May 3, 2014|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref> He is also the former Co-Chairman of the Health Care Committee in the West Virginia State Chamber of Commerce.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evan H. Jenkins (R \u2013 Cabell, 05)|url=http://www.wvlegislature.gov/Senate1/lawmaker.cfm?member=Senator%20Jenkins|website=West Virginia Legislature|accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==West Virginia Legislature==\nJenkins served on both sides of the legislature in Charleston, having first been elected as a member of the [[West Virginia House of Delegates]] in 1994.<ref name=\"Jim Workman\"/> He lost a race for the [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/rothenblog/freshman-class-filled-with-losers/?dcz=|title=Freshman Class Filled With Losers|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nJenkins was then elected to the West Virginia State Senate in 2002, after defeating Democratic incumbent [[Marie Redd]] in the [[primary election]] and former State Senator Thomas Scott in the [[general election]]. In 2006, Jenkins once again defeated Redd in the primary election, and Scott in the general election (with 64% of the vote).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-13942977.html|title=Final results for state, federal legislative races in W.Va.|publisher=|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Jenkins was again re-elected to the West Virginia State Senate, District 5, running unopposed in the general election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chambers|first1=Bryan|title=Jenkins wins 3rd term in Senate|url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/news/x1180430936/Jenkins-wins-3rd-term-in-Senate|accessdate=July 12, 2014|work=Herald-Dispatch|date=May 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2014\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in West Virginia, 2014#District 3}}\nIn July 2013, Jenkins announced he was switching to the Republican Party in preparation for a run at [[West Virginia's 3rd congressional district]] seat, held by 19-term Democrat [[Nick Rahall]].  He had actually grown up as a Republican, but became a Democrat in 1992 prior to his run for the House of Delegates.  On switching parties, Jenkins stated that: \"West Virginia is under attack from Barack Obama and a Democratic Party that our parents and grandparents would not recognize.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/democrat-switches-parties-to-challenge-rahall/|title=Democrat Switches Parties to Challenge Rahall #WV03|date=July 31, 2013|accessdate=July 31, 2013|work=[[Roll Call]]|first=Abby|last=Livingston}}</ref> West Virginia's 3rd district had long been a Democratic stronghold, but had been swept up in the growing Republican tide that had swept the state since the turn of the century. In 2012, it went for [[Mitt Romney]] 66-32 percent, making it the second-most Republican district in the nation to be represented by a Democrat.<ref name=post/>  Jenkins and Rahall had contributed to each other's campaigns in the decade's previous election cycles.<ref name=\"Contributions\">{{cite news | url=http://www.charlestondailymail.com/News/statenews/201307290182 | title=Nick Rahall, Evan Jenkins contributed to each other's campaigns | work=[[Charleston Daily Mail]] | date=July 30, 2013 | accessdate=October 6, 2014 | author=Boucher, Dave}}</ref>\n\nJenkins ran unopposed in the Republican primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pocahontastimes.com/beard-mclaughlin-win-primary-election/|title=Beard, McLaughlin win primary election|publisher=|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref>  He faced Rahall in the general election in November 2014.  An early poll showed Jenkins with a double-digit lead over Rahall.<ref name=post>{{cite news|last=Blake|first=Aaron|title=GOP poll: Longtime Rep. Rahall (D-W.Va.) down double digits|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2014/03/11/gop-poll-longtime-rep-rahall-d-w-va-down-double-digits/|accessdate=May 23, 2014|newspaper=Washington Post|date=March 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Right to Life Committee]], West Virginia Chamber of Commerce, and West Virginians for Life, all of which had previously supported Rahall, supported Jenkins in 2014, and the [[West Virginia Coal Association]] endorsed Jenkins in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huntingtonnews.net/95924|title=West Virginia Coal Association Endorses Evan Jenkins|work=Huntington News|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlestondailymail.com/article/20140916/DM0104/140919414|title=Charleston Daily Mail \u2013 Jenkins receives national pro-life endorsement|publisher=|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref> On October 2, managing editor Kyle Kondik of [[Sabato's Crystal Ball]] said the race was a toss-up, calling it \"Super close, super expensive and super nasty.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2014/10/02/looking-into-the-crystal-ball/|title= Looking into the Crystal Ball|work=West Virginia Metro News|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rothenbergpoliticalreport.com/ratings/house|title=House Ratings|work= The Rothenberg Political Report|accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref>  Rahall outspent Jenkins in the election by a two-to-one ratio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/midterm-elections-2014-live-updates/story?id=26570502|title=Republicans Projected To Seize Control Of The Senate: 2014 Midterm Elections Results Live|author=ABC News|work=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Jenkins defeated Rahall, taking 55% of the vote to 45% \u2013 the second-largest margin of defeat suffered by an incumbent in the 2014 cycle.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2014/west-virginia-elections|title=West Virginia Election Results|publisher=}}</ref>  As a measure of how Democratic much of this district once was, when Jenkins took office on January 3, 2015, he became the first Republican to represent what is now the 3rd since 1957 (the district was numbered as the 4th before 1993), and the first Republican to represent most of the district's southern portion since 1933 (most of which was the [[West Virginia's 5th congressional district|5th district]] before it was eliminated in 1973).<ref>{{cite book|title = The Historical Atlas of Political Parties in the United States Congress|last = Martis|first = Kenneth C.|authorlink =|coauthors =|year = 1989|publisher = Macmillan Publishing Company|location = New York|id =}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title = The Historical Atlas of United States Congressional Districts|last = Martis|first = Kenneth C.|authorlink =|coauthors =|year = 1982|publisher = Macmillan Publishing Company|location = New York|id =}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/biosearch/biosearch.asp |title=Congressional Biographical Directory (CLERKWEB) |publisher= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100423082228/http://bioguide.congress.gov/biosearch/biosearch.asp |archivedate=April 23, 2010 }}</ref> In addition, Jenkins' victory, along with those of [[Alex Mooney]] and [[David McKinley]], meant that West Virginia had an all-Republican House delegation for the first time since 1923.\n\n=== 2016 ===\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in West Virginia, 2016#District 3}}\n[[File:WestVirginia's3rdcongressionaldistrict2016electionresultsbycounty.png|thumb|Map showing the results of the 2016 election in West Virginia's third congressional district by County.]]\nJenkins defeated Democratic candidate Matt Detch<ref>{{Cite web|title = W.Va. features packed ballot for 2016 election|url = http://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/tri_state/west_virginia/w-va-features-packed-ballot-for-election/article_e4610bcc-cabc-11e5-bb95-13d5bfedfee6.html|website = Herald Mail Media|access-date = 2016-02-07}}</ref> in the November 2016 general election with 67.9% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://services.sos.wv.gov/apps/elections/results/results.aspx?year=2016&eid=23&county=Statewide |title=West Virginia Statewide Results General Election \u2013 November 8, 2016 Official Results |publisher=West Virginia Secretary of State|date=November 8, 2016 |accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Committee on Appropriations]]'''\n** [[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Commerce, Justice, Science, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Commerce, Justice, Science, and Related Agencies]]\n** [[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Interior, Environment, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Interior, Environment, and Related Agencies]]\n** [[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on the Legislative Branch|Subcommittee on the Legislative Branch]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==2018 U.S. Senate election==\nOn May 8, 2017, Jenkins announced his intention to [[United States Senate election in West Virginia, 2018|run for the United States Senate]] seat held by [[Joe Manchin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsaz.com/content/news/Jenkins-announces-he-will-challenge-Manchin-for-US-Senate-seat-421655304.html|title=Jenkins to challenge Manchin for U.S. Senate seat|first=WSAZ News|last=Staff|publisher=|accessdate=April 25, 2018}}</ref> His main competitor for the Republican nomination was state Attorney General [[Patrick Morrisey]]. On May 8, 2018, exactly one year after announcing his bid for the Republican nomination, Jenkins lost the primary, coming in second to Morrisey.<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/08/politics/polls-close-west-virginia-indiana/index.html</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\n=== Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) ===\nOn September 5, 2017, President Trump formally rescinded the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) program. DACA allows certain undocumented immigrants who entered the United States as children to receive a renewable two-year period of deferred action from deportation and eligibility for a work permit. Jenkins supported Trump's decision. Jenkins said, \u201cPresident Obama overstepped his constitutional authority by creating the DACA program through an executive order. We are a nation of laws and have a responsibility to secure our borders.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511208398-morrisey-jenkins-both-praise-trump-s-decision-to-rescind-daca|title=Morrisey, Jenkins both praise Trump's decision to rescind DACA|last=Dickerson|first=Chris|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nJenkins opposes federal cap and trade restrictions on coal emissions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailycaller.com/2014/06/04/forty-one-senators-push-for-repeal-of-obamas-cap-and-trade-rule/|title=Forty-One Senators Push For Repeal Of Obama\u2019s Cap-And-Trade Rule|last1=Bastasch|first1=Michael|date=June 4, 2014|work=Daily Caller|accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> He feels that some [[Environmental Protection Agency]] regulations are too strict, such as those affecting the [[Coal#Coal as fuel|coal industry]] and the use of [[wood-burning stove]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdtonline.com/news/rep-jenkins-vows-to-keep-heat-on-agency-over-new/article_643c58e6-c60a-11e4-9dea-93392803f803.html|title=Rep. Jenkins vows to keep heat on agency over new wood-burning regulations|date=March 9, 2015|work=Bluefield Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.loganbanner.com/news/news/152138688/Jenkins-cosponsors-Spruce-Mine-Bill|title=Jenkins cosponsors Spruce Mine Bill|author=|date=March 2, 2015|work=Logan Banner|access-date=March 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402154158/http://www.loganbanner.com/news/news/152138688/Jenkins-cosponsors-Spruce-Mine-Bill|archive-date=April 2, 2015|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s decision to withdraw from the [[Paris Agreement]], saying: \"The Paris accord puts the United States on an uneven playing field, forcing us to make costly reductions, all while countries like China and India make their own rules.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wvgazettemail.com/news-politics/20170601/wv-leaders-praise-withdrawal-from-climate-deal|title=WV leaders praise withdrawal from climate deal|last=Zuckerman|first=Jake|date=June 1, 2017|work=Charleston Gazette-Mail|access-date=June 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Health care ===\nIn May 2017, Jenkins voted for the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act (AHCA)]], the Republican bill to repeal and replace the [[Obamacare|Affordable Care Act (Obamacare)]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/04/us/politics/house-vote-republican-health-care-bill.html|title=How Every Member Voted on the House Health Care Bill|last=Shorey|first=Gregor Aisch, Sarah Almukhtar, Wilson Andrews, Jeremy Bowers, Nate Cohn, K. k Rebecca Lai, Jasmine C. Lee, Alicia Parlapiano, Adam Pearce, Nadja Popovich, Kevin Quealy, Rachel|date=2017-05-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-08-02|last2=Singhvi|first2=Anjali|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.wvgazettemail.com/news-politics/20170504/wv-reps-mooney-jenkins-mckinley-vote-yes-on-ahca|title=WV Reps. Mooney, Jenkins, McKinley vote yes on AHCA|work=Charleston Gazette-Mail|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wvmetronews.com/2017/05/08/jenkins-doing-nothing-on-health-care-wasnt-an-option/|title=Jenkins: Doing nothing on health care \u2018wasn\u2019t an option\u2019|date=2017-05-08|website=WV MetroNews|access-date=2017-08-02}}</ref> saying that he supported \"coverage for pre-existing conditions, mental health care and substance abuse treatment... Under this legislation, West Virginia would have a choice about what will work best for us.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Later in June 2017, Jenkins said that while AHCA allowed states to opt out of the requirement that insurers not discriminate against individuals with preexisting conditions and the requirement that insurers provide \"essential health benefits\", he did not want West Virginia to seek waivers from those requirements.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.wvgazettemail.com/news-politics/20170609/jenkins-clarifies-stance-on-ahca|title=Jenkins clarifies stance on AHCA|work=Charleston Gazette-Mail|access-date=2017-08-02|language=en-US}}</ref> Asked about the nonpartisan [[Congressional Budget Office]]'s estimate that 23 million Americans would lose their insurance under AHCA, Jenkins questioned the accuracy of the CBO's prediction and said that the numbers failed to account for people who will get insurance due to economic growth.<ref name=\":1\" />{{dead link|date=January 2018}}\n\n=== Opioid crisis ===\nIn August 2017, Jenkins discussed the issue of the [[Opioid epidemic|opioid crisis]] with President Trump on [[Air Force One]] on the ride back to Washington after Trump spoke at the National Boy Scout Jamboree. As a member of the House Appropriations Committee, Jenkins said the issue is important to him. He worked to help get hundreds of millions of dollars for treatment, law enforcement and drug courts. Jenkins said, \"In addition, I helped authorize the full $1.6 billion President Trump requested for the southern border wall, which will help stop the flow of [[black tar heroin]] into the United States.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wvrecord.com/stories/511187007-state-leaders-praise-trump-s-declaration-of-national-emergency-in-opioid-crisis|title=State leaders praise Trump's declaration of national emergency in opioid crisis|last=Dickerson|first=Chris|date=2017-08-17|work=West Virginia Record|access-date=2018-02-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJenkins and his wife Elizabeth have three children, two sons and one daughter.<ref name=\"W.Va. Senate 5\"/><ref name=\"Jenkins confirms run for Congress\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jenkins|first1=Evan|title=Evan Jenkins: The nation desperately needs new leadership|url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/opinions/x571850892/Evan-Jenkins-The-nation-desperately-needs-new-leadership|accessdate=July 12, 2014|work=Herald-Dispatch|date=April 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://evanjenkins.house.gov/ Congressman Evan Jenkins] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.evanjenkins.com/ Evan Jenkins for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/West_Virginia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Evan_Jenkins_%5BR-3%5D|Evan Jenkins}}\n* {{ CongLinks | congbio = J000297 | fec = H4WV03070 | votesmart = 8297| congress = evan-jenkins/J000297}}\n* {{C-SPAN|evanjenkins}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060814234935/http://www.marshall.edu/etd/descript.asp?ref=408 Analysis of Jenkin's 2002 victory over Redd.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nick Rahall]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[West Virginia's 3rd congressional district]]|years=2015\u20132018}}\n{{s-vac}}\n|-\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robin Davis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia|West Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current West Virginia statewide political officials}}\n{{WestVirginiaUSRepresentatives}}\n{{USCongRep-start\n| congresses= 114th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]\n| state= [[United States congressional delegations from West Virginia|West Virginia]]}}\n{{USCongRep/WV/114}}\n{{USCongRep/WV/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Auth